[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] This page lists references for Web app manifest members usage on the web.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `background_color` manifest member is used to specify an initial background color for your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] This color appears in the application window before your application's stylesheets have loaded.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `categories` manifest member lets you specify one or more classifications for your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] These categories help users discover your app in app stores.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `description` manifest member is used to explain the core features or functionality of your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] This text helps users understand your app's purpose when viewing it in an app store.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `display` manifest member is used to specify your preferred display mode for the web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The display mode determines how much of the browser UI is shown to the user when the app is launched within the context of an operating system.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] You can choose to show the full browser interface or hide it to provide a more app-like experience.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `display` member is used to determine the developer's preferred display mode for a website.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] It follows a process where the browser falls back to the next display mode if the requested one is not supported.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] In some advanced use cases, this fallback process might not be enough.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `file_handlers` member specifies an array of objects representing the types of files an installed progressive web app (PWA) can handle.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `icons` manifest member is used to specify one or more image files that define the icons to represent your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `id` manifest member is used to specify a unique identifier for your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `launch_handler` member defines values that control the launch of a web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] Currently it can only contain a single value, `client_mode`, which specifies the context in which the app should be loaded when launched.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] For example, in an existing web app client containing an instance of the app, or in a new web app client.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] This leaves scope for more `launch_handler` values to be defined in the future.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `name` manifest member is used to specify the full name of your web application as it's usually displayed to users, such as in application lists or as a label for your application's icon.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `note_taking` member identifies a web app as a note-taking app and defines related information, for example a URL pointing to functionality for taking a new note.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] This enables operating systems to integrate the app's note taking functionality, for example including a "New note" option in the app's context menu, or providing the app as an option for taking a note in other apps.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `orientation` manifest member is used to specify the default orientation for your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] It defines how the app should be displayed when launched and during use, in relation to the device's screen orientation, particularly on devices that support multiple orientations.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `prefer_related_applications` manifest member is used to provide a hint to browsers whether to prefer installing native applications specified in the `related_applications` manifest member over your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `protocol_handlers` member specifies an array of objects that are protocols which this web app can register and handle.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] Protocol handlers register the application in an OS's application preferences; the registration associates a specific application with the given protocol scheme.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] For example, when using the protocol handler `mailto://` on a web page, registered email applications open.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `related_applications` manifest member is used to specify one or more applications that are related to your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] These may be platform-specific applications or Progressive Web Apps.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `scope` manifest member is used to specify the top-level URL path that contains your web application's pages and subdirectories.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] When users install and use your web app, pages *within scope* provide an app-like interface.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] When users navigate to pages outside the app's scope, they still experience the app-like interface, but browsers display UI elements like the URL bar to indicate the change in context.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `scope_extensions` manifest member is used to extend the scope of a web app to include other origins.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] This allows multiple domains to be presented as a single web app.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `screenshots` manifest member lets you specify one or more images that showcase your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] These images help users preview your web app's interface and features in app stores.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `serviceworker` member specifies a serviceworker that is Just-In-Time (JIT)-installed and registered to run a web-based payment app providing a payment mechanism for a specified payment method in a merchant website.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] See `Web-based Payment Handler API` for more details.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `share_target` manifest member allows installed Progressive Web Apps (PWAs) to be registered as a share target in the system's share dialog.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `short_name` manifest member is used to specify a short name for your web application, which may be used when the full `name` is too long for the available space.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `shortcuts` manifest member is used to specify links to key tasks or pages within your web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] Browsers can use this information to create a context menu, which is typically displayed when a user interacts with the web app's icon.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `start_url` manifest member is used to specify the URL that should be opened when a user launches your web application, such as when tapping the application's icon on their device's home screen or in an application list.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] The `theme_color` member is used to specify the default color for your web application's user interface.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] This color may be applied to various browser UI elements, such as the toolbar, address bar, and status bar.
[src:progressive-web-apps/manifest-reference] It can be particularly noticeable in contexts like the task switcher or when the app is added to the home screen.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The **`Notification`** interface of the Notifications API is used to configure and display desktop notifications to the user.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] These notifications' appearance and specific functionality vary across platforms but generally they provide a way to asynchronously provide information to the user.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Creates a new instance of the `Notification` object.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] A string representing the current permission to display notifications.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The maximum number of actions supported by the device and the User Agent.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The actions array of the notification as specified in the constructor's `options` parameter.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] A string containing the URL of an image to represent the notification when there is not enough space to display the notification itself such as for example, the Android Notification Bar.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] On Android devices, the badge should accommodate devices up to 4x resolution, about 96 by 96 px, and the image will be automatically masked.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The body string of the notification as specified in the constructor's `options` parameter.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Returns a structured clone of the notification's data.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The text direction of the notification as specified in the constructor's `options` parameter.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The URL of the image used as an icon of the notification as specified in the constructor's `options` parameter.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The URL of an image to be displayed as part of the notification, as specified in the constructor's `options` parameter.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The language code of the notification as specified in the constructor's `options` parameter.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] When set, activating the notification navigates to this URL instead of firing the `click` or `notificationclick` event.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Specifies whether the user should be notified after a new notification replaces an old one.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] A boolean value indicating that a notification should remain active until the user clicks or dismisses it, rather than closing automatically.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Specifies whether the notification should be silent — i.e., no sounds or vibrations should be issued regardless of the device settings.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The ID of the notification (if any) as specified in the constructor's `options` parameter.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Specifies the time at which a notification is created or applicable (past, present, or future).
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] The title of the notification as specified in the first parameter of the constructor.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Specifies a vibration pattern for devices with vibration hardware to emit.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Requests permission from the user to display notifications.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Programmatically closes a notification instance.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Fires when the user clicks the notification.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Fires when the user closes the notification.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Fires when the notification encounters an error.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] Fires when the notification is displayed.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] We no longer show a live sample on this page, as Chrome and Firefox no longer allow notification permissions to be requested from cross-origin `<iframe>`s, with other browsers to follow.
[src:progressive-web-apps/notification] To see an example in action, check out our To-do list example (also see the app running live).
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] A **progressive web application** (**PWA**), or **progressive web app**, is a type of web app that can be installed on a device as a standalone application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] PWAs are installed using the offline cache of the device's web browser.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] PWAs were introduced from 2016 as an alternative to native (device-specific) applications, with the advantage that they do not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] They can be used on a range of different systems, including desktop and mobile devices.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Publishing the app to digital distribution systems, such as the Apple App Store, Google Play, or the Microsoft Store on Windows, is optional.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Because a PWA is delivered in the form of a webpage or website built using common web technologies including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and WebAssembly, it can work on any platform with a PWA-compatible browser.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] As of 2025, PWA features are supported to varying degrees by Google Chrome, Apple Safari, Brave, Firefox for Android, Microsoft Edge, and Firefox for Windows.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] At Apple's Worldwide Developers Conference in 2007, Steve Jobs announced that the iPhone would "run applications created with Web 2.0 Internet standards".
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] No software development kit (SDK) was required, and the apps would be fully integrated into the device through the Safari browser engine.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] This model was later switched to the App Store, as a means of appeasing frustrated developers.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] In October 2007 Jobs announced that an SDK would be launched the following year.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] As a result, although Apple continued to support web apps, the vast majority of iOS applications shifted toward the App Store.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Beginning in the early 2010s dynamic web pages allowed web technologies to be used to create interactive web applications.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Responsive web design, and the screen-size flexibility it provides have made PWA development more accessible.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Continued enhancements to HTML, CSS, and JavaScript allowed web applications to incorporate greater levels of interactivity, making native-like experiences possible on a website.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] It was intended to be an open-source operating system for running web apps as native apps on mobile devices.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Firefox OS was based on the Gecko rendering engine with a user interface called Gaia, written in HTML5.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] The development of Firefox OS ended in 2016, and the project was completely discontinued in 2017, although a fork of Firefox OS was used as the basis of KaiOS, a feature phone platform.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Google then put significant efforts into promoting PWA development for Android.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Firefox introduced support for service workers in 2016, and Microsoft Edge and Apple Safari followed in 2018, making service workers available on all major systems.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] By 2019, PWAs were supported by desktop versions of some browsers, including Microsoft Edge (on Windows) and Google Chrome (on Windows, macOS, ChromeOS, and Linux).
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] In December 2020, Firefox for desktop abandoned the implementation of PWAs (specifically, removed the prototype "site-specific browser" configuration that had been available as an experimental feature).
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] A Firefox architect noted: "The signal I hope we are sending is that PWA support is not coming to desktop Firefox anytime soon." Mozilla supports PWAs on Android and plans to keep supporting it.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Firefox version 143.0, released in September 2025, added support for PWA on Windows.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps are all designed to work on any browser that is compliant with the appropriate web standards.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] As with other cross-platform solutions, the goal is to help developers build cross-platform apps more easily than they would with native apps.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps employ the progressive enhancement web development strategy.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Some progressive web apps use an architectural approach called the App Shell Model.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] In this model, service workers store the Basic User Interface or "shell" of the responsive web design web application in the browser's offline cache.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] This model allows for PWAs to maintain native-like use with or without web connectivity.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] This can improve loading time, by providing an *initial static frame*, a layout or architecture into which content can be loaded progressively as well as dynamically.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] There are many technologies commonly used to create progressive web apps.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] A web application is considered a PWA if it satisfies the installation criteria, thus can work offline and can be added to the device's home screen.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] To meet this definition, all PWAs require at minimum a manifest and a service worker.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Other technologies may be used to store data, communicate with servers or execute code.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] This metadata is crucial for an app to be added to a home screen or otherwise listed alongside native apps.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] iOS Safari partially implements manifests, while most of the PWA metadata can be defined via Apple-specific extensions to the meta tags.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] These tags allow developers to enable full-screen display, define icons and splash screens, and specify a name for the application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] A service worker is a web worker that implements a programmable network proxy that can respond to web/HTTP requests from the main document.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] It is able to check the availability of a remote server, cache content when that server is available, and serve that content to the document later.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Service workers, like any other web workers, work separately from the main document context.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Service workers can handle push notifications and synchronize data in the background, cache or retrieve resource requests, intercept network requests and receive centralized updates independently of the document that registered them, even when that document is not loaded.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Service workers go through a three-step lifecycle of Registration, Installation and Activation.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Registration involves telling the browser the location of the service worker in preparation for installation.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Installation occurs when there is no service worker installed in the browser for the web app, or if there is an update to the service worker.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Activation occurs when all of the PWA's pages are closed, so that there is no conflict between the previous version and the updated one.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] The lifecycle also helps maintain consistency when switching among versions of a service worker since only a single service worker can be active for a domain.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] WebAssembly allows precompiled code to run in a web browser, at near-native speed.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Thus, libraries written in languages such as C can be added to web apps.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Announced in 2015 and first released in March 2017, WebAssembly became a W3C recommendation on December 5, 2019 and it received the Programming Languages Software Award from ACM SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] is a WHATWG standard API that enables key–value storage in modern browsers.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] (that enables storage that persists across sessions).
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] is a W3C standard database API available in all major browsers.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] objects and any structures representable as a string.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] providing additional constructs around it.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] In 2017, Twitter released Twitter Lite, a PWA alternative to the official native Android and iOS apps.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] According to Twitter, Twitter Lite consumed only 1–3% of the size of the native apps.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Starbucks provides a PWA that is 99.84% smaller than its equivalent iOS app.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] After deploying its PWA, Starbucks doubled the number of online orders, with desktop users ordering at about the same rate as mobile app users.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] A 2018 review published by Forbes, found that users of Pinterest's PWA spent 40% more time on the site compared to the previous mobile website.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Ad revenue rates also increased by 44%, and core engagements by 60%.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Flipkart saw 60% of customers who had uninstalled their native app return to use the Flipkart PWA.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Lancôme saw an 84% decrease in time until the page is interactive, leading to a 17% increase in conversions and a 53% increase in mobile sessions on iOS with their PWA.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Since a PWA does not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms and is available to users via the web, it is not necessary for developers to release it over digital distribution systems like the Apple App Store, Google Play, Microsoft Store, or Samsung Galaxy Store.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] The major app stores support the publication of PWAs to varying degrees.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Google Play, Microsoft Store, and Samsung Galaxy Store support PWAs, but Apple App Store does not.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-app] Microsoft Store publishes some qualifying PWAs automatically (even without app authors' requests) after discovering them via Bing indexing.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] A **progressive web app** (PWA) is an app that's built using web platform technologies, but that provides a user experience like that of a platform-specific app.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] Like a website, a PWA can run on multiple platforms and devices from a single codebase.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] Like a platform-specific app, it can be installed on the device, can operate while offline and in the background, and can integrate with the device and with other installed apps.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] The PWA guides provide conceptual explanations of different aspects of PWAs.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] They're intended to help you understand what kinds of things are possible with PWAs, and to provide enough pointers to help you understand how to achieve them.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] An introduction to PWAs, comparing them with traditional websites and with platform-specific apps, and outlining their main features.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] One of the defining aspects of a PWA is that it can be installed on the device, and then appears to users as a platform-specific app, a permanent feature of their device which they can launch directly from the operating system like any other app.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] In this guide we'll explore what "installable" means, what a PWA needs to provide for it to be installable, and how you can customize the install experience.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] This guide covers how users can install and uninstall PWAs on their devices.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] In this guide, we'll introduce a set of technologies that enable a PWA to provide a good user experience even when the device has intermittent network connectivity and to perform operations in the background, even when the main app is not running.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] An overview of the APIs that enable a PWA to cache resources locally, and some common strategies used by PWAs to implement offline functionality.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] PWAs should adapt to different browsers and devices, be accessible, have good performance, and integrate well with the operating system.
[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] This guide provides a list of best practices to help you make sure your PWA is as good as it can be.
