[src:progressive-web-apps/progressive-web-apps] An API for PWAs installed on desktop operating systems that enables hiding the default window title bar, enabling displaying the app over the full surface area of the app window.
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] A **web application manifest**, defined in the Web Application Manifest specification, is a JSON text file that provides information about a web application.
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] The most common use for a web application manifest is to provide information that the browser needs to install a progressive web app (PWA) on a device, such as the app's name and icon.
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] A web application manifest contains a single JSON object where the top-level keys are called *members*.
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] This section lists reference pages for manifest members that are documented on MDN.
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] All members are optional in the specification, but some applications require some members to be present.
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] For example, PWAs must provide certain manifest members.
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] The `.webmanifest` extension is specified in the Media type registration section of the specification (the response of the manifest file should return `Content-Type: application/manifest+json`).
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] Browsers generally support manifests with other appropriate extensions like `.json` (`Content-Type: application/json`).
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] If the manifest requires credentials to fetch, the `crossorigin` attribute must be set to `use-credentials`, even if the manifest file is in the same origin as the current page.
[src:progressive-web-apps/web-manifest] In some browsers and operating systems, a splash screen is displayed when an installed PWA is launched.
